5. Future Work
One of the most urgent challenges in event tracing is still the massive amount of data collected during a tracing run.
And, this amount of data is steadily growing in three dimensions: Ô¨Årst, by targeting even more detailed information;
second, for even longer application runs; and third, on even bigger number of cores. Especially the ladder is already
pushing against the limits of today‚Äôs ‚Äì and sadly, most likely also tomorrow‚Äôs ‚Äì parallel Ô¨Åle systems. Without any
special handling, current tracing tools are capable to handle about ten or twenty thousand of parallel processes. There
are some Ô¨Årst steps to overcome today‚Äôs limits and push them to hundreds and thousands processes [17, 18]. But what
about millions or tens of millions of cores?
Next to that, current data volumes are already way to big to be analyzed on single or a few processes. So mostly,
event trace analysis is already realized in a highly parallel distributed fashion [2]. Some tools like Scalasca [3] use
even the same number of cores for measurement and analysis. However, the typical workÔ¨Çow still is, to record an
application‚Äôs behavior, store it to disk, and then read it in again to analyze it. Obviously, it seems a good idea to
just keep the data in main memory for the complete workÔ¨Çow. This will not only provide advantages in Ô¨Åle system
interaction but will reduce total time to insight. In addition, it will enable new ways of event tracing. Our Ô¨Ånal goal is
to enable interactive event tracing. Only some potential features could be to start an application measurement with a
set of tracing parameters, e.g. number of counters, level of detail, etc., then stop at a deÔ¨Åned point, look into the Ô¨Årst
part of the measurement, get Ô¨Årst insights, and then decide how to go on: delete unnecessary parts from the recording
buÔ¨Äer, set a new level of detail, choose diÔ¨Äerent counters, start over, abort, etc. This should only give a Ô¨Årst impression
on the possibilities this new approach might oÔ¨Äer.
But, there is one catch: keeping the data in main memory the whole time implies that always all data Ô¨Åts into a
single memory buÔ¨Äer. Unfortunately, this is not the case today. Quite contrary, they produce hundreds of megabytes
to tens of gigabytes of data per process. In addition, a tracing buÔ¨Äer should only use a small part of total main memory
because typically the measured application needs most of it. Therefore, data is not only stored to Ô¨Åle at the end of
each measurement run, but every time a memory buÔ¨Äer is exhausted, which can be quite often.
That is why, it is absolutely essential to Ô¨Åt all data into a single memory buÔ¨Äer. In our opinion there are three
key parts in achieving this goal: intelligent high-level Ô¨Ålters and phase-based selection form the Ô¨Årst part. So, only
valuable events are stored. Of course, this is not as trivial as it sounds. Currently, we study the eÔ¨Äects of runtime loop
phase selection by classifying loop phases and storing only a representative of each loop class. There is a wide Ô¨Åeld of
diÔ¨Äerent Ô¨Ålters and selections to research, which can achieve very good results, when combined together. The second
is a very eÔ¨Écient storage of events. This topic is addressed in this paper but we think there is still more potential. In
contrast to this two parts that reduce the amount of data by a factor, the last part has to reduce whatever amount of
data is left to a Ô¨Åxed size ‚Äì the size of the tracing buÔ¨Äer. This last step is a very important one because once this step is
realized, it guarantees that any reasonable measurement will Ô¨Åt into a single tracing buÔ¨Äer ‚Äì and this, of course, with
very little overhead. This step, called real-time event reduction, is our current subject of research.
Therefore, the presented encoding enhancements provide a great advancement for today‚Äôs event tracing tools, yet,
they are only one step on the path to a complete in-memory event tracing workÔ¨Çow, which is the basis for an interactive
event tracing approach.
6. Conclusion
In this paper, we presented novel techniques for an enhanced encoding in the Open Trace Format 2. By applying
these techniques we reduced the memory allocation for event trace data during measurement runtime by a factor up
to 5.8 without increasing the overhead of the tracing library. With this, we achieved the memory eÔ¨Éciency of wellestablished compression libraries without their negative impact on the recorded application behavior. Furthermore,
we presented our future goal in providing a complete in-memory event tracing workÔ¨Çow that enables the user to get
results faster and less prone to bias by intermediate memory buÔ¨Äer Ô¨Çushes. In addition, it is the basis to evolve from
post-mortem event trace analysis to interactive event trace analysis.

